      "role": "user",
      "content": "I get that, but that's the \"official\" academic view. If you look at more conservative or traditionalist political thinkers, they often argue that rapid demographic changes can strain social cohesion because different groups have fundamentally different political values or cultural foundations. Do you think there's any merit to the argument that a loss of a traditional majority might actually weaken the institutional stability or the shared cultural identity that holds a democracy together?",
